\par 'Merely the violence of pleasure,' Marvin replied gallantly.
\par 'Your words are too glib by half,' said the Lady Catarina. 'I believe it has been noted that the longest and wiliest tongues conceal the shortest and least adequate of Weapons.'
\par 'Your ladyship does me injustice,' Marvin said. 'For I dare say my Weapon is e
minently capable of the uses it may encounter, sharp enough to penetrate the best defence in the world, and durable enough for repeated stabbings. And, quite apart from such utilitarian uses, it has learned from me certain infallible tricks, the which it 
would be my respectful pleasure to show your ladyship.'
\par 'Nay, keep your Weapon in its scabbard,' the lady quoth, indignantly, but with sparkling eyes. 'Me likes not the sound of 't; for braggart's steel is ever pliable tin, shiny to the eye yet damnably malleable to the touch.'
\par 'I beg of thee but to touch the edge and point,' Marvin said, 'and thus submit thy raillery to th' test of Usage.'
\par She shook her pretty head. 'Know, sir, that such Pragmatics are for greybeard philosophers with rheumy eyes; a lady relies upon her intuition.'
\par 'Lady, I worship thy intuition,' Marvin responded.
\par 'Why, sir, what wouldst Thou, the Prepossessor of a dubious Weapon of indetermined length and uncertain temper, know of a woman's intuition?'
\par 'Lady, my heart tells me that it is exquisite and ineffable, and possessed of a pleasing shape and delicate fragrance, and that--'
\par 'Enough, sir!' the Lady Catarina cried, blushing hotly and fanning herself furiously with a Japanese fan whose corrugated surface portrayed the Investiture of the Iichi.
\par Both fell silent. They had been conversing in the old Language of Courtly Love, in which symbolic apostrophe played so important a part. In those days it was deemed no breach of the etiquette for even the best-bred and most demure of young ladies to
 thus converse; theirs was not a frightened age.
\par But now a shadow of seriousness had fallen over the two participants. Marvin glowered, fingering the grey steel buttons of his white lace shirt. And the Lady Catarina looked troubled. She wore a panelled gow
n of dove tulip with slashings of chrome red; and, as was the custom, the neckline was cut fashionably low to reveal the firm rosy swelling of her little abdomen. Upon her feet were sandal-pumps of ivory-coloured damask; and her hair, piled high upon a ja
de ratouelle, was adorned with a garland of spring snippinies. Never in his life had Marvin seen so beautiful a sight.
\par 'Can we not cease this ceaseless play of word-foolery?' Marvin asked quietly. 'May we not say that which is in our hearts, 'stead of fencing thus with heartless ingenuities?'
\par 'I dare not!' the Lady Catarina murmured.
\par 'And yet, you are Cathy, who loved me once in another time and place,' Marvin said inexorably, 'and who now plays me for the unacknowledged gallant.'
\par 'You must not speak of that which once had been,' Cathy said, in a frightened whisper.
\par 'Yet still you loved me once!' Marvin cried hotly. 'Deny me this an you find it false!'
\par 'Yes,' she said in a failing voice. 'I loved thee once.'
\par 'And now?'
\par 'Alas!'
\par 'But speak and tell me reason!'
\par Nay, I cannot!'
\par 'Will not, rather.'
\par 'As thee wish; the choice is servant to the heart.'
\par 'I would not have you believe that,' she said softly.
\par 'No? Then surely the desire is father to the intent,' Marvin said, his face gone hard and pitiless. 'And standing thus in familial relationship, not even the wisest of men would deny that Love is inbonded to its half-sister Indifference, and Faithfulness 
is thrall to the cruel stepmother, Pain.'
\par 'Can you so consider me?' she cried weakly.
\par 'Why, Lady, you leave me choiceless,' Marvin responded in a voice of ringing bronze. 'And thus my barque of Passion is Derelict upon a Sea of Memory, blown off its rightfu
l course by the fickle wind of Indifference, and driven towards the rockbound Coast of Agony by the inexorable Tide of Human Events.'
\par 'And yet, I would not have it thus,' Catarina said, and Marvin thrilled to hear even so mild an affirmation of that which he had considered lost beyond recall.
\par 'Cathy--'
\par 'Nay, it cannot be,' she cried, recoiling in evident agony, her colour high and her abdomen rising and falling with the emotion within her. 'You know not of the wretched circumstances of my situation.'
\par 'I dem
and to know!' Marvin cried, then whirled, his hand darting to his sword. For the great oaken door of his chamber had swung noiselessly open, and there, leaning negligently in the doorway, a man stood with arms folded over his chest and a half-smile playin
g across his thin, bearded lips.
\par 'In faith! We are undone!' Catarina cried, her hand pressed to her trembling abdomen.
\par 'Sir, what would thou?' Marvin asked hotly. 'I demand to know thy name, and the reason for this most ungentle and unseemly investiture!'
\par '
